&gt;&gt; Kenneth Naito:
Well, actually,

00:32:02.270 --> 00:32:05.460
since you mentioned
styles, and it's--

00:32:05.460 --> 00:32:08.850
well, what you define
as classical,

00:32:08.850 --> 00:32:13.600
there are many different eras of
music that define a classical.

00:32:13.600 --> 00:32:15.700
So like the piece
I played, the Bach,

00:32:15.700 --> 00:32:17.040
that is a baroque style piece

00:32:17.040 --> 00:32:22.790
because it was written during
the 1600's when Bach was alive.

00:32:22.790 --> 00:32:26.600
And so there's Baroque, there's
also classical which is defined

00:32:26.600 --> 00:32:30.590
as like Mozart, Mozart was a
classical, there's romantic,

00:32:30.590 --> 00:32:35.550
just much more-- as the title
suggests, gets more romantic

00:32:35.550 --> 00:32:36.850
in that it's, there's--

00:32:36.850 --> 00:32:38.870
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Mid
to late 19th century.

00:32:38.870 --> 00:32:41.640
&gt;&gt; Kenneth Naito: Right, and
then there's 20th century music

00:32:41.640 --> 00:32:44.350
which is the 1900's, and
then we have modern music.

00:32:44.350 --> 00:32:48.640
So it's not just--
classical is a very broad term

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:52.790
for the different types of music
that are in the classical--

00:32:52.790 --> 00:32:56.730
So, but sorry, going back
to your question, yeah,

00:32:56.730 --> 00:32:58.290
this violin is really good.

00:32:58.290 --> 00:33:00.700
It was really good
for the Bach I think.

00:33:00.700 --> 00:33:07.230
Because as Nate said, the dark
tones help the mood of the piece

00:33:07.230 --> 00:33:10.440
which is kind of somber,

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:14.790
but at the same time there's
a glimpse of hope and peace.

00:33:14.790 --> 00:33:19.300
So I think this violin
really helped to make

00:33:19.300 --> 00:33:20.920
that the mood of the piece.

00:33:20.920 --> 00:33:22.430
So, yeah.

00:33:22.430 --> 00:33:23.900
&gt;&gt; Nate Growler: I like it

00:33:23.900 --> 00:33:29.350
when I was just playing the tune
Garfield's Blackberry Blossom,

00:33:29.350 --> 00:33:31.730
it's old time tune.

00:33:31.730 --> 00:33:35.750
And there's kind of like a
rawness in old time music,

00:33:35.750 --> 00:33:38.350
and this violin has
that sort of raw quality

00:33:38.350 --> 00:33:40.710
to it, in a really good way.

00:33:40.710 --> 00:33:44.880
Because it's a beautiful sound
it makes, but you're able

00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:49.440
to kind of draw out this sort of
dark raw tone that I think fits

00:33:49.440 --> 00:33:53.210
that style really really well.

00:33:53.210 --> 00:33:58.860
Anyway, the Irish, it sounded
great, I mean-- it's sort of a--

00:33:58.860 --> 00:34:03.110
I see Irish players kin of
really be able to draw a lot

00:34:03.110 --> 00:34:06.010
of sound without using much bow,

00:34:06.010 --> 00:34:08.470
and you can play the
strings really softly

00:34:08.470 --> 00:34:11.090
and get a nice sound.

00:34:11.090 --> 00:34:14.480
So you can really kind of
create that dynamic thing well.

00:34:14.480 --> 00:34:16.180
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So this is a
very responsive instrument?

00:34:16.180 --> 00:34:17.480
&gt;&gt; Nate Growler: Absolutely.

00:34:17.480 --> 00:34:18.780
&gt;&gt; Kenneth Naito: Oh yeah.

00:34:18.780 --> 00:34:20.840
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: You get just
a real range of different--

00:34:20.840 --> 00:34:23.770
it does what you ask it
to do as a performer?

00:34:23.770 --> 00:34:25.070
&gt;&gt; Nate Growler: I
think so, definitely.

00:34:25.070 --> 00:34:26.410
Yeah.

00:34:26.410 --> 00:34:28.980
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Do either of
you play an American fiddle now?

00:34:28.980 --> 00:34:30.370
&gt;&gt; Kenneth Naito:
Actually I do, yes.

00:34:30.370 --> 00:34:33.200
The violin I'm currently
playing on is

00:34:33.200 --> 00:34:36.610
by the maker named Jeff Philips.

00:34:36.610 --> 00:34:38.540
It's a beautiful violin.

00:34:38.540 --> 00:34:41.970
It was actually made
I think two years ago,

00:34:41.970 --> 00:34:44.430
so it's a very recent
violin, but he made it here--

00:34:44.430 --> 00:34:47.970
he lives in America
and he made the violin,

00:34:47.970 --> 00:34:50.030
it's a beautiful modern violin.

00:34:50.030 --> 00:34:52.300
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: So, he's
continuing the tradition

00:34:52.300 --> 00:34:56.900
that David was talking about
of fine American violin-making.

00:34:56.900 --> 00:34:58.200
&gt;&gt; Kenneth Naito: Oh yeah.

00:34:58.200 --> 00:35:01.820
There are many amazing,
wonderful modern violins.

00:35:01.820 --> 00:35:05.580
If you ask me this question ten
years ago I would be a little

00:35:05.580 --> 00:35:07.550
bit questionable because I feel

00:35:07.550 --> 00:35:11.890
like the violins made ten years
ago were still a little bit iffy

00:35:11.890 --> 00:35:15.340
in terms of the quality,
but now the art

00:35:15.340 --> 00:35:19.240
of violin making has really
gone up in quality and--

00:35:19.240 --> 00:35:21.170
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: But this
was made 100 years ago.

00:35:21.170 --> 00:35:25.550
&gt;&gt; Kenneth Naito: Oh, well, age
also helps to a violin as well.

00:35:25.550 --> 00:35:27.740
As a violin gets
older, it also--

00:35:27.740 --> 00:35:29.040
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: It matures.

00:35:29.040 --> 00:35:30.610
&gt;&gt; Kenneth Naito: Yeah, the
sound also becomes much--

00:35:30.610 --> 00:35:35.440
it changes as well and I think
this violin has very well.

00:35:35.440 --> 00:35:37.580
&gt;&gt; Nancy Groce: Is there
anything else you'd like to say

00:35:37.580 --> 00:35:40.040
